tables.name: SalesLT.SalesOrderDetail
tables.description: The SalesLT.SalesOrderDetail table contains detailed information about individual sales order transactions. Each entry in this table corresponds to a specific product within a sales order, including details such as the quantity ordered, the unit price, and any discounts applied. This table is crucial for understanding the specifics of sales transactions, permitting analysis of sales performance, product demand, and financial calculations related to sales orders.

columns.name: SalesOrderID
columns.definition: The SalesOrderID column in the SalesLT.SalesOrderDetail table represents a unique identifier for each sales order. This column is of integer type and serves as a primary key, ensuring each sales order can be uniquely identified. It is used to link details about individual sales orders, such as order quantity, product ID, unit price, and other relevant order information.

columns.name: SalesOrderID
columns.definition: The SalesOrderID column in the SalesLT.SalesOrderDetail table is an integer that uniquely identifies each sales order. It serves as a primary key to link each order detail to a specific sales order. This column is essential for querying order-specific details and is used to join with other tables containing order information. The values in this column are unique identifiers corresponding to individual sales transactions.

columns.name: SalesOrderDetailID
columns.definition: The SalesOrderDetailID column in the SalesLT.SalesOrderDetail table is a unique identifier for each sales order detail entry. It is an integer and serves as part of the primary key along with SalesOrderID. Each value in this column uniquely identifies a particular detail of a sales order, ensuring there are no duplicate entries in the table. This column is essential for distinguishing between different order details associated with various sales orders.

columns.name: OrderQty
columns.definition: The OrderQty column in the SalesLT.SalesOrderDetail table represents the quantity of a specific product ordered in each sales transaction. It is an integer value stored as a smallint, indicating how many units of the product were included in the order. This column is essential for understanding the volume of products sold in individual orders and is crucial for sales analysis and inventory management.

columns.name: ProductID
columns.definition: The ProductID column in the SalesLT.SalesOrderDetail table is an integer that represents the unique identifier for a product associated with a sales order detail. Each value in this column corresponds to a specific product that is included in a sales order. This column is essential for identifying and linking the product details to the sales transactions. The data in this column typically includes product identifiers that are used to retrieve additional information about the products from related tables.

columns.name: UnitPrice
columns.definition: The UnitPrice column in the SalesLT.SalesOrderDetail table represents the retail price of a single unit of a product in a sales order. This column is of the money data type, indicating it stores monetary values with precision. The values in this column are used to calculate the LineTotal for each order, combined with OrderQty and UnitPriceDiscount. This column does not allow null values and is essential for assessing the cost per unit of items ordered in the sales transactions.

columns.name: UnitPriceDiscount
columns.definition: The UnitPriceDiscount column in the SalesLT.SalesOrderDetail table represents the discount applied to the unit price of a product in a sales order. The data type is money, indicating that it holds monetary values for the discount amount. Typical values in this column range from 0 to any percentage value representing the discount applied to the unit price. This column is useful for calculating the discounted price of a product in a sales transaction.

columns.name: LineTotal
columns.definition: The LineTotal column in the SalesLT.SalesOrderDetail table represents the total monetary value for a line item in a sales order. This value is calculated as the product of the order quantity, the unit price, and any applicable discounts for that specific product. The data type for this column is numeric and it reflects the final amount owed for that line item after applying any discounts. This column is essential for summarizing the financial details of each order line item in the sales order.

columns.name: rowguid
columns.definition: The rowguid column in the SalesLT.SalesOrderDetail table is a unique identifier for each record in the table. It is of type uniqueidentifier, which ensures that each value in this column is globally unique. This column is typically used to uniquely distinguish records independently of the primary keys and is useful for maintaining uniqueness across different systems or databases.

columns.name: ModifiedDate
columns.definition: The ModifiedDate column in the SalesLT.SalesOrderDetail table stores the date and time when a specific sales order detail was last updated. This column uses the datetime data type, capturing both the date and time information. The ModifiedDate column is essential for tracking changes and maintaining the history of sales order details, which can be useful for auditing and reporting purposes.

tables.name: SalesLT.SalesOrderHeader
tables.description: The SalesLT.SalesOrderHeader table contains information about individual sales orders within an organization. Each entry uniquely identifies a sales order and includes details such as order dates, status, shipping methods, and financial details like subtotal, tax, and total due amounts. The table also links sales orders to customers, shipping addresses, and payment information, facilitating comprehensive tracking and management of sales transactions. This information is crucial for fulfilling orders, analyzing sales patterns, and generating financial reports.

columns.name: SalesOrderID
columns.definition: SalesOrderID is an integer column in the SalesLT.SalesOrderHeader table that uniquely identifies each sales order. It serves as the primary key for the table, ensuring that each entry is distinct. This column is essential for querying specific sales orders and linking them to relevant transactional data within the database.

columns.name: RevisionNumber
columns.definition: The "RevisionNumber" column in the "SalesLT.SalesOrderHeader" table contains integer values of type tinyint that represent the revision number of a sales order. It is used to indicate the number of times an order has been modified or revised. Each time the order is changed after its initial creation, this number is incremented by 1. This helps track the history and updates made to the sales order over time.

columns.name: OrderDate
columns.definition: The OrderDate column in the SalesLT.SalesOrderHeader table contains the dates on which sales orders were placed. This date is recorded in the datetime format and represents the time when the customer confirmed the order. This column is crucial for tracking the timing of sales activities, analyzing order patterns over time, and generating reports based on sales data within specific date ranges.

columns.name: DueDate
columns.definition: The DueDate column in the SalesLT.SalesOrderHeader table represents the date by which an order is expected to be completed and delivered. This column is of the datetime data type, meaning it stores both the date and time information. DueDate is critical for scheduling and fulfilling orders on time and can be used to track order deadlines or to assess late orders for further analysis.

columns.name: ShipDate
columns.definition: ShipDate is a datetime column in the SalesLT.SalesOrderHeader table that records the date on which an order was shipped. This date is typically after the OrderDate and before or on the DueDate, indicating when the order left the warehouse or shipping facility. It is crucial for tracking logistics and ensuring timely delivery to the customer. Analysis of this column helps in understanding shipping performance and operational efficiency.

columns.name: Status
columns.definition: The "Status" column in the "SalesLT.SalesOrderHeader" table is a tinyint data type that represents the current state of a sales order. It typically contains numerical values corresponding to different statuses, indicating whether the order is pending, processed, shipped, or canceled. This column is used to filter or categorize sales orders based on their progress or completion levels. The value of this column is integral in tracking the workflow and fulfillment of sales orders.

columns.name: OnlineOrderFlag
columns.definition: The "OnlineOrderFlag" column in the SalesLT.SalesOrderHeader table is a bit (boolean) data type that indicates whether the sales order was placed online. A value of 1 (true) signifies that the order was placed via an online platform, while a value of 0 (false) means the order was placed through other means, such as in-store or by phone. This flag helps in distinguishing online sales from offline sales, which can be useful for reporting and analysis purposes.

columns.name: SalesOrderNumber
columns.definition: The SalesOrderNumber column in the SalesLT.SalesOrderHeader table contains unique alphanumeric identifiers for each sales order. These identifiers are prefixed with 'SO' followed by a numeric sequence, ensuring each order can be distinctly referred to. This column is essential for tracking and managing individual sales orders and serves as a reference for linking related data within the sales process.

columns.name: PurchaseOrderNumber
columns.definition: The column "PurchaseOrderNumber" in the "SalesLT.SalesOrderHeader" table contains unique identifiers for purchase orders associated with sales orders. Each value is a string that follows a specific format, typically starting with "PO" followed by a series of digits. This column is used to link sales orders to their corresponding purchase orders, facilitating tracking and management of orders within the sales process. This data is crucial for identifying and querying specific purchase orders related to sales transactions.

columns.name: AccountNumber
columns.definition: The AccountNumber column in the SalesLT.SalesOrderHeader table contains alphanumeric values that uniquely identify customer accounts associated with sales orders. These account numbers follow a specific pattern and serve as a reference for tracking financial information related to sales transactions. This column is crucial for linking sales orders to specific customer accounts, facilitating order management and financial reporting processes.

columns.name: CustomerID
columns.definition: CustomerID is an integer column in the SalesLT.SalesOrderHeader table that uniquely identifies each customer associated with a sales order. This column is not a primary key but serves as a foreign key linking to customer-specific data in other tables, enabling the tracking and management of customer-related information for each sales order. The CustomerID is crucial for filtering queries to retrieve or manipulate sales order records specific to a particular customer.

columns.name: ShipToAddressID
columns.definition: The ShipToAddressID column in the SalesLT.SalesOrderHeader table contains integer values that represent the unique identifier for the address where the order is to be shipped. This column is used to link a sales order to a specific shipping address stored in an address table. The ShipToAddressID helps in determining the delivery location for each sales order and is crucial for coordinating logistics and ensuring accurate delivery.

columns.name: BillToAddressID
columns.definition: The BillToAddressID column in the SalesLT.SalesOrderHeader table stores the unique identifier for the address where the billing information should be sent for each sales order. This column is of integer type and links to the specific address details in another table, ensuring the correct billing address is associated with each order. It is used to determine the billing location for the customer and is critical for invoicing and financial transactions related to the order.

columns.name: ShipMethod
columns.definition: The ShipMethod column in the SalesLT.SalesOrderHeader table indicates the method used to ship the sales order. This column holds information about the carrier name or shipping service chosen for delivering the order to the customer. The data type of this column is nvarchar, which means it stores variable-length string data containing the name or identifier of the shipping method used.

columns.name: CreditCardApprovalCode
columns.definition: The CreditCardApprovalCode column in the SalesLT.SalesOrderHeader table contains the approval code received from the credit card authorization process for a given sales order. This column is of type varchar and stores the alphanumeric code that indicates approval status from the credit card issuer. This code is essential for processing and validating transactions involving credit card payments.

columns.name: SubTotal
columns.definition: The SubTotal column in the SalesLT.SalesOrderHeader table represents the monetary amount of the subtotal for each sales order before taxes and freight charges are added. This column is of money data type, indicating that it holds currency values, typically representing the sum of all sale items on an order. The values in this column are used to calculate the TotalDue amount by adding tax and freight charges. It provides a detailed breakdown of the sales order value excluding additional charges.

columns.name: TaxAmt
columns.definition: The TaxAmt column in the SalesLT.SalesOrderHeader table represents the monetary amount of tax associated with a sales order. The values are of the money data type, indicating they are expressed in currency. This column is used to store the calculated tax applied to each order, based on the relevant tax rate and order subtotal. The TaxAmt column is crucial for financial calculations and reporting related to sales taxes for each order.

columns.name: Freight
columns.definition: The Freight column in the SalesLT.SalesOrderHeader table contains the shipping cost associated with each sales order. This column stores monetary values representing the cost incurred for transporting goods from the seller to the buyer. The data type for this column is money, which ensures the values are stored with precision. This column is crucial for calculating the total order cost and is used in the financial aspects of order management.

columns.name: TotalDue
columns.definition: The TotalDue column in the SalesLT.SalesOrderHeader table represents the final amount due for a sales order. This amount includes the subtotal of all items in the order, along with any taxes and freight charges. The data type for this column is money, ensuring that it can accurately store decimal values representing currency. This column is used to determine the total financial liability of the customer for a specific order.

columns.name: Comment
columns.definition: The "Comment" column in the SalesLT.SalesOrderHeader table is an nvarchar type that is used to store additional notes or remarks related to a sales order. This column allows users to provide supplementary information that is not captured by other columns in the table. The data in this column can vary widely, including but not limited to, special instructions, customer feedback, or internal notes. Since this column can contain diverse textual information, it is useful for adding context or comments about the sales order.

columns.name: rowguid
columns.definition: The "rowguid" column in the SalesLT.SalesOrderHeader table contains uniqueidentifier values that serve as a unique global identifier for each row. This column is used to ensure the uniqueness of each record across different tables and databases, which is particularly useful for synchronization and merging operations. The data in this column is typically not used for business logic directly but is crucial for maintaining data integrity and traceability.

columns.name: ModifiedDate
columns.definition: The ModifiedDate column in the SalesLT.SalesOrderHeader table represents the date and time when the sales order record was last modified. This column contains datetime values indicating the most recent update to any information within each sales order entry. It is used to track changes and maintain the integrity of the sales order data by logging the last modification timestamp. This information is crucial for auditing purposes and ensuring that the most current data is reflected in the system.
